[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] It’s been available across browsers since October 2017.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] The **`WebAssembly`** JavaScript object acts as the namespace for all WebAssembly-related functionality.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Unlike most other global objects, `WebAssembly` is not a constructor (it is not a function object).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] You can compare it to `Math`, which is also a namespace object for mathematical constants and functions, or to `Intl` which is the namespace object for internationalization constructors and other language-sensitive functions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Indicates an error during WebAssembly decoding or validation.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Represents a global variable instance, accessible from both JavaScript and importable/exportable across one or more `WebAssembly.Module` instances.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] This allows dynamic linking of multiple modules.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Indicates an error during module instantiation (besides traps from the start function).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] An object whose `buffer` property is a resizable `ArrayBuffer` that holds the raw bytes of memory accessed by a WebAssembly `Instance`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Contains stateless WebAssembly code that has already been compiled by the browser and can be efficiently shared with Workers, and instantiated multiple times.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Error type that is thrown whenever WebAssembly specifies a trap.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] An array-like structure representing a WebAssembly Table, which stores references, such as function references.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] An object that represents a type of WebAssembly exception.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] A WebAssembly exception object that can be thrown, caught, and rethrown both within and across WebAssembly/JavaScript boundaries.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] A built-in `WebAssembly.Tag` representing exceptions thrown in the JavaScript host — it allows exceptions thrown in JavaScript to be handled from inside a Wasm module.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Compiles a `WebAssembly.Module` from WebAssembly binary code, leaving instantiation as a separate step.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Compiles a `WebAssembly.Module` directly from a streamed underlying source, leaving instantiation as a separate step.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] The primary API for compiling and instantiating WebAssembly code, returning both a `Module` and its first `Instance`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Compiles and instantiates a WebAssembly module directly from a streamed underlying source, returning both a `Module` and its first `Instance`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Validates a given typed array of WebAssembly binary code, returning whether the bytes are valid WebAssembly code (`true`) or not (`false`).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] The following example (see our instantiate-streaming.html demo on GitHub, and view it live also) directly streams a Wasm module from an underlying source then compiles and instantiates it, the promise fulfilling with a `ResultObject`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] Because the `instantiateStreaming()` function accepts a promise for a `Response` object, you can directly pass it a `fetch()` call, and it will pass the response into the function when it fulfills.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/global-objects-webassembly] The `ResultObject`'s `.instance` property is then accessed, and the contained exported function invoked.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] This article explains the concepts behind how WebAssembly works including its goals, the problems it solves, and how it runs inside the web browser's JavaScript engine.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] WebAssembly (abbreviated as *Wasm*) is a low-level bytecode format originally designed for the web.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] It is not primarily intended to be written by hand, rather it is designed to be an effective compilation target for source languages like C, C++, Rust, etc.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] This has huge implications for the web platform — it provides a way to run code written in multiple languages on the web at near-native speed, with client apps running on the web that previously couldn't have done so.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] What's more, you don't even have to know how to create WebAssembly code to take advantage of it.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] WebAssembly modules can be imported into a web (or Node.js) app, exposing WebAssembly functions for use via JavaScript.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] JavaScript frameworks could make use of WebAssembly to confer massive performance advantages and new features while still making functionality easily available to web developers.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Historically, the VM has been able to load only JavaScript.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] This has worked well for us as JavaScript is powerful enough to solve most problems people have on the Web today.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] We have run into performance problems, however, when trying to use JavaScript for more intensive use cases like 3D games, Virtual and Augmented Reality, computer vision, image/video editing, and a number of other domains that demand native performance (see WebAssembly use cases for more ideas).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Additionally, the cost of downloading, parsing, and compiling very large JavaScript applications can be prohibitive.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Mobile and other resource-constrained platforms can further amplify these performance bottlenecks.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] WebAssembly is a different language from JavaScript, but it is not intended as a replacement.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] With the advent of WebAssembly appearing in browsers, the virtual machine that we talked about earlier will now load and run two types of code — JavaScript AND WebAssembly.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The different code types can call each other as required — the WebAssembly JavaScript API wraps exported WebAssembly code with JavaScript functions that can be called normally, and WebAssembly code can import and synchronously call normal JavaScript functions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] In fact, the basic unit of WebAssembly code is called a module and WebAssembly modules are symmetric in many ways to ES modules.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] There are several key concepts needed to understand how WebAssembly runs in the browser.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] All of these concepts are reflected 1:1 in the WebAssembly JavaScript API.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The JavaScript API provides developers with the ability to create modules, memories, tables, and instances.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Given a WebAssembly instance, JavaScript code can synchronously call its exports, which are exposed as normal JavaScript functions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Arbitrary JavaScript functions can also be synchronously called by WebAssembly code by passing in those JavaScript functions as the imports to a WebAssembly instance.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Since JavaScript has complete control over how WebAssembly code is downloaded, compiled and run, JavaScript developers could even think of WebAssembly as just a JavaScript feature for efficiently generating high-performance functions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] In the future, WebAssembly modules will be loadable just like ES modules (using `<script type='module'>`), meaning that JavaScript will be able to fetch, compile, and import a WebAssembly module as easily as an ES module.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Above we talked about the raw primitives that WebAssembly adds to the Web platform: a binary format for code and APIs for loading and running this binary code.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Now let's talk about how we can use these primitives in practice.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The WebAssembly ecosystem is at a nascent stage; more tools will undoubtedly emerge going forward.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Two of the many options for creating Wasm code are an online Wasm assembler or Emscripten.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] These are great resources for people who are trying to figure out where to start, but they lack some of the tooling and optimizations of Emscripten.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The Emscripten tool is able to take just about any C/C++ source code and compile it into a Wasm module, plus the necessary JavaScript "glue" code for loading and running the module, and an HTML document to display the results of the code.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Emscripten transforms the compiled result of clang+LLVM into a Wasm binary.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] By itself, WebAssembly cannot currently directly access the DOM; it can only call JavaScript, passing in integer and floating point primitive data types.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Thus, to access any Web API, WebAssembly needs to call out to JavaScript, which then makes the Web API call.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Emscripten therefore creates the HTML and JavaScript glue code needed to achieve this.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The JavaScript glue code is not as simple as you might imagine.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] For a start, Emscripten implements popular C/C++ libraries like SDL, OpenGL, OpenAL, and parts of POSIX.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] These libraries are implemented in terms of Web APIs and thus each one requires some JavaScript glue code to connect WebAssembly to the underlying Web API.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] So part of the glue code is implementing the functionality of each respective library used by the C/C++ code.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The glue code also contains the logic for calling the above-mentioned WebAssembly JavaScript APIs to fetch, load and run the Wasm file.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] The generated HTML document loads the JavaScript glue file and writes stdout to a `<textarea>`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] If the application uses OpenGL, the HTML also contains a `<canvas>` element that is used as the rendering target.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] It's very easy to modify the Emscripten output and turn it into whatever web app you require.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] You can find full documentation on Emscripten at emscripten.org, and a guide to implementing the toolchain and compiling your own C/C++ app across to Wasm at Compiling from C/C++ to WebAssembly.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] Do you want to build your own compiler, or your own tools, or make a JavaScript library that generates WebAssembly at runtime?
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] In the same fashion as physical assembly languages, the WebAssembly binary format has a text representation — the two have a 1:1 correspondence.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] You can write or generate this format by hand and then convert it into the binary format with any of several WebAssembly text-to-binary tools.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] For a simple guide on how to do this, see our Converting WebAssembly text format to Wasm article.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] It is also possible to write Rust code and compile over to WebAssembly, thanks to the tireless work of the Rust WebAssembly Working Group.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] You can get started with installing the necessary toolchain, compiling a sample Rust program to a WebAssembly npm package, and using that in a sample web app, over at our Compiling from Rust to WebAssembly article.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] For web developers who want to try WebAssembly without needing to learn the details of C or Rust, staying in the comfort of a familiar language like TypeScript, AssemblyScript will be the best option.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] AssemblyScript compiles a strict variant of TypeScript to WebAssembly, allowing web developers to keep using TypeScript-compatible tooling they are familiar with — such as Prettier, ESLint, VS Code IntelliSense, etc.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] You can check its documentation on https://www.assemblyscript.org/.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/guides-concepts] This article has given you an explanation of what WebAssembly is, why it is so useful, how it fits into the web, and how you can make use of it.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] The **`WebAssembly.instantiate()`** static method allows you to compile and instantiate WebAssembly code.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] A typed array or `ArrayBuffer` containing the binary code of the Wasm module you want to compile.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] The `WebAssembly.Module` object to be instantiated.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] An object containing the values to be imported into the newly-created `Instance`, such as functions or `WebAssembly.Memory` objects.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] There must be one matching property for each declared import of the compiled module or else a `WebAssembly.LinkError` is thrown.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] An object containing compilation options.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] An array of strings that enables the usage of JavaScript builtins in the compiled Wasm module.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] The strings define the builtins you want to enable.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] Currently the only available value is `"js-string"`, which enables JavaScript string builtins.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] A string specifying a namespace for imported global string constants.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] This property needs to be specified if you wish to use imported global string constants in the Wasm module.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] If a `module` is passed, returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `WebAssembly.Instance` object.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] After fetching some WebAssembly bytecode using fetch, we compile and instantiate the module using the `WebAssembly.instantiate()` function, importing a JavaScript function into the WebAssembly Module in the process.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] We then call an Exported WebAssembly function that is exported by the `Instance`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] The following example (see our index-compile.html demo on GitHub, and view it live also) compiles the loaded simple.wasm byte code using the `WebAssembly.compileStreaming()` method and then sends it to a worker using `postMessage()`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] In the worker (see `wasm_worker.js`) we define an import object for the module to use, then set up an event handler to receive the module from the main thread.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] When the module is received, we create an instance from it using the `WebAssembly.instantiate()` method and invoke an exported function from inside it.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-instantiate] This example enables JavaScript string builtins and imported global string constants when compiling and instantiating the Wasm module with `instantiate()`, before running the exported `main()` function (which logs `"hello world!"` to the console).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The **`WebAssembly.Memory`** object is a resizable `ArrayBuffer` or `SharedArrayBuffer` that holds raw bytes of memory accessed by a `WebAssembly.Instance`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Both WebAssembly and JavaScript can create `Memory` objects.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] If you want to access the memory created in JS from WebAssembly, or vice versa, you can export the memory from the module to JavaScript or import memory from JavaScript to the module when it is instantiated.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Originally you could only perform memory operations on a single memory in the Wasm module, so while multiple `Memory` objects could be created, there wasn't any point in doing so.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] More recent implementations allow WebAssembly memory instructions to operate on a specified memory.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] For more information see Multiple memories in *Understanding WebAssembly text format*.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Returns the buffer contained in the memory.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Increases the size of the memory instance by a specified number of WebAssembly pages (each one is 64KiB in size).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] There are two ways to get a `WebAssembly.Memory` object.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The first way is to construct it from JavaScript.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The following snippet creates a new WebAssembly Memory instance with an initial size of 10 pages (640KiB), and a maximum size of 100 pages (6.4MiB).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Its `buffer` property will return an `ArrayBuffer`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The following example (see memory.html on GitHub, and view it live also) fetches and instantiates the loaded "memory.wasm" bytecode using the `WebAssembly.instantiateStreaming()` function, while importing the memory created in the line above.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] It then stores some values in that memory, exports a function, and uses the exported function to sum those values.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Note the use of `DataView` to access the memory so we always use little-endian format.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] Another way to get a `WebAssembly.Memory` object is to have it exported by a WebAssembly module.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] This memory can be accessed in the `exports` property of the WebAssembly instance (after the memory is exported within the WebAssembly module).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The following example imports a memory exported from WebAssembly with the name `memory`, and then prints out the first element of the memory, interpreted as a `Uint32Array`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] By default, WebAssembly memories are unshared.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] This memory's `buffer` property will return a `SharedArrayBuffer`.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly-memory] The following snippet creates a new WebAssembly Memory instance with a 64-bit address type.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:web-assembly-js-api/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
